<li id="cite_note-Tola&amp;Dragonetti-307"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Tola&amp;Dragonetti_307-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Tola, Fernando. Dragonetti, Carmen (2009). <i>"Brahamanism and Buddhism: Two Antithetic Conceptions of Society in Ancient India."</i> p. 26: "This also implied the denial of the Shruti provided with characteristics which grant it the status of a substance. All this carried with itself also the negation of the authority of all the sacred texts of Brahmanism. Buddhism does not acknowledge to them any value as ultimate criterion of truth, as depository of the norms which regulate man’s conduct as a member of society and in his relations with the Gods. Buddhism ignores the Shruti, the very foundation of Brahmanism."</span>
